				<Shape ID="82" UniqueID="{B8E69DC0-9CB6-4033-9F78-206AE95DDB3F}" Name="Sheet.82" NameU="Sheet.82">
					<Text>Do I need a fuse on the negative wire to my radio?</Text>
					<XForm>
						<PinX Unit="MM">5.807086614173229</PinX>
						<PinY Unit="MM">8.692913385826770</PinY>
					</XForm>
				</Shape>
				<Shape ID="83" UniqueID="{7F05D3CA-C62C-4DE0-8391-C487037AA266}" Name="Sheet.83" NameU="Sheet.83">
					<Text>It won’t hurt if you install a fuse on the negative lead, and the wiring harness that ships with most Amateur mobiles has two fuses. The fuse on the negative (ground) lead is only really required on installations that connect directly to the vehicle battery.  The fuses should be installed close to the battery.

The reason for the fuse, is that if the vehicle grounding from the battery to the car frame/engine should fail, either partially or completely, the radios negative lead “could” in some cases become the return path to the battery for the vehicle, causing the wire to burn.

This is not an issue for radios connected to power supplies, the vehicle chassis or batteries not in a vehicle. ALWAYS FUSE THE POSITIVE LEAD!</Text>
					<XForm>
						<PinX Unit="MM">5.818897637795276</PinX>
						<PinY Unit="MM">7.460629921259843</PinY>
					</XForm>
				</Shape>
